 the diverse political and cultural consequences of a variety of texts, from eighteenth-century oriental tales to mystic poetry of the fin de siecle and from translation proper to its ethnological, mythographic, and religious variants.Searching for translation’s trace enables a broader, more complex understanding of intellectual exchange in imperial culture as well as a more nuanced awareness of the dialectical relationship between colonial policy and nineteenth-century literature. Rangarajan argues that while bearing witness to the violence that underwrites translation in colonial spaces, we should also remain open to the irresolution of translation, its unfixed nature, and its ability to transform both languages in which it works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aIndic literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aTranslating and interpretingzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aTranslating and interpretingzIndiaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aColonialism.  aExoticism.  aIndia.  aOriental Tale.  aOrientalism.  aVictorian Literature.  aimperialism.  aromanticism.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z97831111896040 cprintz978082326361540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823263639?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823263639423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823263639/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d